title: Linear rails for the Printable Unicorn

description.text:
A while back I printed a copy of the Printable unicorn then sat around scratching my head about what to use as a linear rail. A while later I was pulling apart an old DVD drive when I found two 2.9mm rods.
Armed with my trusty digital calipers and pro desktop, I reverse engineered the print head of the printable unicorn with two arms extending backwards with two verticle guide holes, then designed two side brackets to hold the rails.
I used melted ABS (with auto paint thinners) to glue the side rails to the body of the unicorn and then assembled it. 
When I'm done I will cut off the rails so that they don't extend past the top of the side rails!
Now I just have to get it working! ;)
PS: Sorry about the size of the .avi, I'm just recovering from a catastrophic SSD failure and I havenâ€™t got around to installing my file conversion software!

• Obtain rods.
  • Print 2 side brackets and one print head.
  • I drilled out the holes in he brackets to obtain a tight fit and the the pen holder to obtain free and easy movement with little play.
  • Glue side rails to the body section of the unicorn body using melted ABS and wait until it it is dry.
    5.On each side, slide the rod through the top brace then through the appropriate hole on the print head then down through the lower brace.

This Active Cooling System is made for the Wanhao Duplicator 4 series and Flashforge. This variation is made to fit blower type fans that is 40mm big (24V), 20mm thick, although 10mm thickness would probably work too.

UPDATE! (V2)

Hey guys, if you have downloaded the previous duct, please redownload V2. I noticed there's some problems with the fan position being too high that it hits the casing when the extruder is being homed. This has been corrected in V2, it now sits below the case with a certain gap space. Also I have changed the fan bracket to the bottom, so now there's no need to print supports for it. Notice that the 3 holes on the screws mount are significantly smaller than the fan's screw holes, this is intentional. Use woodscrews (Screws with sharp ends) and screw it into the screw mounts to securely fasten the fan. Also I have redesigned the entire vent so that fan sits comfortably on top of it. Overall, this design is vastly superior to the first version.

Why Active Cooling?

Most of the time when it comes to insufficient heat, the solution is simple, increase the temp (bed/nozzle), wall up the printer sides so retain heat. However while increasing heat could help with bed adhesion and extrusion, plastic also needs time to cool to properly layer and bridge. If you spot areas in your print where lines are drooping or bowling upwards, your plastic isn't cool enough.

Active Cooling Helps

Active Cooling enables the plastic to cool down much quicker enabling bridging longer distances possible. Also when printing at higher speeds, active cooling enables layers to harden before the next layer is printed. Without Active Cooling, your nozzle could press against the previous still molten layer, thus causing it to bowl up and ruin the print.

Wiring the Active Cooling 3rd Fan

There's a tutorial on how to wire the fan in the 5th image panel, however this is just a suggestion. I added this because other active cooling projects did not detail much on this, and I had to find it out for myself. As for why this is a suggestion, this method is just tapping off power from the motherboard fan to power your AC fan. This means it is always on, regardless of printer states. This is sufficient for active cooling, but you might want to embark further into transferring the wires to the extra fan port, enabling you to control the fan using gcode.

Printing Settings

Without ACS, it's better to print with supports. I went with 0.2mm with 30% infill.

You have to stick your arm up a hatch in the wheelhouse to get to the lamp.
You can't see what you're doing, you can hardly move your hand and the lamp is held hard with two springs so it's next to impossible to remove it by hand.
So I decided to make a little tool, and it worked way above all expectation.

In addition to the plastic parts you need:

  • two 2.5 mm2 (blue) cable shoes
  • two short (5mm) M3 screws
  • two long (35mm) M3 screws
  • two springs
  • a pair of pliers
  • an M3 tap
  • and a cordless drill makes the threading easier.

How to build it:
Print the plastic parts (use thick walls.)
Remove the blue plastic from the cable shoes. While holding the round part of the cable shoe hard with the pliers, use the tap to thread the hole. It will split it a bit, but no worries, just use the pliers to squeeze it together again. You still have enough thread to make the screw stick.
Then use the tap to make threads for the long screws in the bottom/base part.
Then stick the cable shoes into the top/lamp holder part and fasten them with the short screws.
And finally assemble the bottom and top parts with the long screws and the springs.

How to use it:
Push the outer/lower part of the tool onto the lamp; pushing the springs that is holding the lamp apart.
Then push the center/top part onto the lamp's connector.
Then just pull the whole thing out.

This is a simple mount I created for my Suzuki Bandit 1200S from year 2003. I was looking for a way to charge the batteries of my navigation system. So I bought a socket for usual car charging cables. So far so good. But where to mount this thing?
The provided mounting piece was designed to mount it on the handle bar. I do not like it when there are too much thing mounted to the handlebar. So it needed to be put somewhere else. So one option left was screwing it to the plastik cover in the cockpit. But then I would have to put holes in it. Finally I designed this simple thing to mount it in the middle of the cockpit. There is one center connection between the frame and the plastik cover. The advantage of this mounting position is that it is always at a fixed position. When you move the handlebar the cables dont move. So this adds a lot extra to the lifetime on this thing (on my old motorcycle the cable failed almost every 600km because it was moving with every move of the handlebar). The socket I used is this:

description.text:
Recently started a new summer night job cleaning buses. We use a potable backpack style battery powered vacuum. The annoying problem is that we need to be able to quickly switch from the floor attachment to the brush attachment to clean the seats. There is no easy way to hold the brush head and it has been forgotten a few times. The quick fix was to 3d print a clip that would hold the brush head onto the main shaft of the vacuum handle. It works great. There were a few designs on here that had the right idea but did not fit my liking, so i designed my own. Enjoy.

p.s. i have designed a "bonus" item. I drafted up a all-in-one brush head with built in clip that you can print if your brush head has replaceable and removable bristles. I have not tried printing this one yet, but it should work.

title: Lulzbot Extruder Mod for Printing Flexible Filaments

description.text:
This extruder mod allows you to print with some flexible materials with a Lulzbot Taz 5, Taz 6, or Mini standard extruder (maybe other printers too if they use the same extruder). Just put the part under the idler bearing and through your filament (see attached picture). This part prevents the flexible filament from popping out of the extruder since it is so flexible.

This part also works with the standard extruders of the FlexyDually or Dual Extruder, allowing your FlexyDually to print two different flexible materials or turning your Dual Extruder into a FlexyDually. I attached a few pictures I did with my Dual Extruders and FlexyDually using my mod.

I have tested this mod with the following NinjaTek materials:

Cheetah: This material is very new and is as flexible and strong as SemiFlex. It is better than SemiFlex because it can print much faster and doesn't need glue when printing on a PEI bed. This is the main filament I recommend using with this mod and it works perfect with the standard Lulzbot Cura print profiles for Cheetah: http://ninjatek.com/products/cheetah/

SemiFlex: Superseded by Cheetah, but if you already have some, it works okay with this mod. I recommend printing slower than the SemiFlex Cura print profiles. I have gotten some perfect prints with SemiFlex using this mod, but it is not nearly as consistent as Cheetah.

NinjaFlex: I have done some okay prints using this filament, but nothing that good. You have to print really slow (much slower than default NinjaFlex Cura profiles created by Lulzbot), and it still does not work that well. I don't really recommend using this material with my mod unless you already have some NinjaFlex lying around. You may be able to get some decent prints but no promises. I have heard of some people having success with the mod and NinjaFlex though, so your milage may vary!

Remember to use some PVA based glue stick on your PEI bed if printing with NinjaFlex or SemiFlex because it can stick to the bed too well without the glue and damage the PEI. Also, if you're having trouble extruding try messing with your idler tension.

You can download the Lulzbot made profiles here: https://devel.lulzbot.com/print-profiles/cura/ Make sure to go to your respective printers flexible extruder section to download the profile. Ex for the Mini: https://devel.lulzbot.com/print-profiles/cura/Mini_flexystruder_v2/ Change the nozzle size from 0.6mm to 0.5mm!

title: 1.625" Exhaust Header Fabrication kit - Plastic Snap kit
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Finally, custom header fabrication is easy to do with the help of your 3d printer. No more spending over 4 figures for a plastic snap kit you might use once or twice.

Tube bends snap together for ease of customization when laying out a new header or exhaust design for your next motorized project.

Tubes have bend radius printed on sides for ease of identification, I also printed the different bends in different colours to help identify the different types.

Each bend block is equivalent to a 22.5deg pc.. So 4 pcs will give you a perfect 90deg bend.

They also have angle location marks/notches every 30 deg to help keep track of your compound bends, and make it easy to re assemble and mark once you start tacking with real stainless or steel piping.

This kit package comes with 1.625 Diameter tubes with centerline bend radius of 2", 2.5", 3" and 4", 1" straight, and a 1" straight with closed end for mounting to a header plate.

I have also included the die templates so you can make the holding jig and accurately cut the tubes on a band saw.

The inserts can be printed, but it is recommended to make the base plate and pivot pin out of metal.

This is my v3 style of this snap kit, and the snap fit works fantastic when printed on my zortrax M200. I spend a few weeks printing samples and revisions until I got the fit perfect, and the overall kit just as what I needed.

I am also working on 1.75" and 2.00" diameter snap kits, that use the same internal snap size, so you can snap together any of the different pipe diameters together..

I also have some nice 2.5" dia bends and straights for easy going exhaust layout and planning. "Coming soon" :)

Have a snap attack!

Printer:

Zortrax M200

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.19mm

Infill:

Full

Notes:

ABS filament

Having built small header systems and exhaust systems in the past, one of the most difficult parts of a well built system is planning and initial mock up. Most of the time it is guessing what fits and trial and error.. Which works but ends up with a lot of scrap cuts and bends and aggravation.. Being able to quickly print and snap together what you need for mock up makes these fun fabrication projects 1000% more efficient :)

You also can begin using exotic materials such as stainless or titanium, with minimal waste.. Just plan and cut once!

This is an AK-styled safety selector for the CZ Scorpion EVO 3. This selector was inspired by the "HB Industries AK style selector".

This file should be printed so that the selector lies flat on the print bed surface (should require 180 flip). If the hole doesn't print at proper size ream it open with a .108 bit (or 1/8 although it'll be a bit loose).

This is a work in progress. Any problems please let me know and I will address them as quickly as possible. Thank you!

Change log:
1.01 - Relocated set screw to actually allow the safety to be installed (oops).
1.02 - Relocated screw hole again, angle was too sharp. This should be on the money.
1.03 - Relocated screw hole... again... This time angle was good, but was printing 2mm too high which caused delaminating and fitment issues. Also opened up hole to a slightly larger size to accommodate different printers.
1.04 - Some users reported the switch was sitting too close to the bump on the trigger pack so the higher was increased by 2mm, this should give good clearance on. Kept 1.3 if you prefer the closer feel.
1.05 - Added various left side versions. The left side of the CZ Scorpion has the bolt catch/release lever so I had a couple ideas on how to overcome this. These include the "stubby" which is chopped short. The "thin" which removes the bulkiness of the whole thing and makes it, well, thin. Third version is "mid support" which leaves that bulkiness in the middle, but allows the bolt catch to not interfere. Note: it is difficult to interact with the bolt catch while it is in the 'fire' position. I can't change this because this is how the AK Selector is meant to function since the AK does not have a bolt release (let alone a left side safety).

The CoB stem cap system began as a simple contest entry on Pinshape on June 3rd 2016. I've always wanted to use that area of my bike for something functional and cool. At first my goal was humble: Transport a 16oz paper coffee cup on my bike without spilling all over myself. Hence, the CoB or Coffee on Bike was born. Shortly after making my first prototype, I realized I could put all sorts of things on the base. So, I've been doing just that. I have made a coffee cup holder that will hold a 16oz paper cup and, along with the stopper, I don't spill all over myself, but I have also made an accessory bar, a mount for my phone case (with my phone in it), a Garmin mount and a donut holder. There's much more I'll put on the CoB...bike prows come to mind...but enough of that. For now this is my entry in Pinshape's contest. Man, oh man, do I want a Form 2.

description.text:
I wanted to use the vacuum here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:941551 But I didn't want to glue the quick connect piece to the Intex cover that usually connects to the outlet that goes to towards the filter pump. Instead, I decided to make this piece, which replaces the Intex piece.

After I designed it, I found: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:179352 which is essentially the same thing I have uploaded here. I almost just downloaded it instead of printing mine. Then I saw that it was untested and didn't include the source .scad file. I tweaked my design and started it printing.... and at the same time (give or take the 8 hours I was away from Thingiverse), the author uploaded the .scad file! JJanssen's thing is still untested so I'm publishing my version. I've tested it my version and it works well.

You will need an o-ring over the quick connector. I used one measuring 11mm (7/16") ID, 16mm (5/8") OD, 2.5mm (3/32") thick. You can get 100 for around $2.50 on Amazon (search for #111 o-rings) or around 10 for around $2.50 at most hardware stores.

If you are modifying the .scad file, make sure you have the knurling library and the metric thread library.

Update 7/26/2016: Oops. Looks like the threads weren't actually attached to the rest of the adapter (though they must have been close enough to print as one or for Cura to fix it automatically). I've updated both the .scad and .stl files.

Note that if you have two outlets that run from the pool to the filter/pump (plus the third that runs back from the pump to the pool) then you need to either stop up the outlet that you don't have the printed adapter hooked to (which is what I have done) or print two adapters, hook them both to a Y adapter, and then to the vacuum piece (this should work better but I have not tested it).

But the thread was not correct for my pool, it was some mm too big and the thread dents didn't even touch :( That lead me to rewrite the whole thing (that's always good even to don't forget openscad ;)
My question is... how can it be that the outlet thread was different from mine? Looking your pictures it seems the same... Weird! I think it's unlikely that Intex have different threads... or I'm wrong?
